Upon [[The Clash]]'s early appearance at the [[Sex Pistols]] [[The Screen On The Green|Screen on the Green]] concert, [[Charles Shaar Murray]], an ''[[NME]]'' critic, produced a damning review of the band:

:The Clash are the kind of garage band who should be returned to the garage immediately, preferably with the engine running,{{Sfn|Murray 2003}}{{Sfn|Westway 2001}}{{Sfn|Needs|2004}} which would undoubtedly be more of a loss to their friends and families than to either rock or roll.{{Sfn|Screen on the Green}}{{Sfn|Salewicz|2006|p=162}}

:Followed by:

:Their guitarist on the extreme left, allegedly known as [[Joe Strummer]], has good moves but he and the band are a little shaky on ground that involves starting, stopping and changing chords at approximately the same time.{{Sfn|Salewicz|2006|p=162}}

The Clash reacted immediately by writing the song "Garageland",{{Sfn|Salewicz|2006|p=162}} whose opening verses are: "''Back in the garage with my bullshit detector'' / ''[[Carbon monoxide]] makes sure it's effective''", followed by the chorus: "''We're a garage band'' / ''We come from garageland''", and concluding with "''Back in the garage''".{{sfn|Coon|1977}}

Another theme in the song is about the band signing to [[CBS Records]] on 25 January 1977 for Â£100,000.{{Sfn|Gray|2005|p=216}}  The music press and fans criticized The Clash for having "sold out" to the establishment.{{Sfn|Gray|2005|p=217}}  [[Mark Perry (musician)|Mark Perry]], founder of the leading London punk periodical, ''[[Sniffin' Glue]]'', let loose with what he would later call his "big quote": "Punk died the day The Clash signed to CBS."{{Sfn|Gray|2005|p=218}}  This was evidenced in the verses: "''Meanwhile things are hotting up in the West End alright'' / ''Contracts in the offices and groups in the night'' / ''My bumming slumming friends have got new boots'' / ''And someone just asked me if the group would wear suits''", and, after the chorus, with the following lines: "''I don't want to know about what the rich are doing'' / ''I don't want to go to where the rich are going'' / ''They think they're so clever, they think they're so right'' / ''But the truth is only known by gutter snipes''".{{sfn|Coon|1977}}

"Garageland", as well as the majority of the band's [[The Clash (album)|debut studio album]], was conceived on the 18th floor of a [[Council house|council high rise]] on London's [[Harrow Road]], in a flat that was rented by [[Mick Jones (The Clash)|Jones]]' grandmother, who frequently went to see the band rehearsing.{{Sfn|NME 1991}}  The song was recorded at [[CBS]] Whitfield Street Studio No. 3 on 27 February 1977. The tapes for the entire album were delivered to CBS at the start of March and the recording was released in the United Kingdom through [[CBS Records]] on 8 April 1977. The album was engineered by CBS staff engineer Simon Humphrey and produced by Clash live [[Audio engineering|soundman]] Mickey Foote.{{Sfn|Mojo Classic|p=32}}

==Appearances==
The song made its live debut on 10â11 March 1977, on the first and second night of an early gig at The Coliseum in [[Harlesden]], [[London]], where the band was supported by [[Subway Sect]], [[Buzzcocks]], and [[The Slits]].{{Sfn|Harlesden Roxy 1977}}  From that moment to 1985, the song has become a stable part of the setlists of their future tours and concerts, and has graced stages all over the world.  Among the most important venues, concert halls and arenas there were:
* [[De Montfort Hall]] in [[Leicester]] (1977),{{Sfn|Knowles|2003|p=89}}
* the [[Lyceum Theatre, London]] (1978),{{Sfn|Knowles|2003|p=89}}
* the [[Agora Theatre and Ballroom|Agora]] in [[Cleveland]] (1979),{{Sfn|Knowles|2003|p=89}}
* the [[Palladium (New York City)|New York Palladium]] (1979),{{Sfn|Knowles|2003|p=90}}
* the [[Capitol Theatre (Passaic)|Capitol Theatre]] in [[Passaic, New Jersey]] (1980),{{Sfn|Knowles|2003|pp=90â91}}
* the [[Orpheum Theatre (Boston, Massachusetts)|Orpheum Theatre]] in [[Boston]] (1980),{{Sfn|Knowles|2003|p=91}}
* the [[Hammersmith Palais]] in London (1980),{{Sfn|Knowles|2003|p=91}}
* the [[ThÃ©Ã¢tre Mogador]] in [[Paris]] (1981),{{Sfn|Knowles|2003|p=94}}
* the [[Brixton Academy]] in London (1982 & 1985),{{Sfn|Knowles|2003|pp=96â97, 100}}
* the [[RiverCentre|Saint Paul Civic Center Arena]] in [[St Paul, Minnesota]] (1982),{{Sfn|Knowles|2003|p=97}}
* the [[Hovet|Johanneshovs Isstadion]] in [[Stockholm]] (1984),{{Sfn|Knowles|2003|p=98}}
* the [[ÃlysÃ©e Montmartre|Espace Ballard]] in Paris (1984),{{Sfn|Knowles|2003|p=99}}
* the Orange arena at the [[Roskilde Festival]] of 1985 in [[Denmark]].{{Sfn|Knowles|2003|p=101}}

"Garageland" was first featured as the last track of the band's debut album as well as in its 1979 U.S. release. It also is featured in many unofficial and semi-official bootlegs such as the 1992 release of ''U.S.A. 1979''.{{Sfn|U.S.A. 1979 1992}}  It was featured in the 1980 film release ''[[Rude Boy (film)|Rude Boy]]'', where it was performed live at Rehearsal Rehearsals, but the audio was re-recorded at [[Wessex Studios]],{{Sfn|Rude Boy 1980}} and on ''[[The Punk Rock Movie]]'', directed and filmed by [[Don Letts]] mainly at [[The Roxy]] club in [[Super 8 mm film|Super 8]] in the autumn of 1977 during The Clash's ''White Riot'' tour, and published in DVD format in 1992.{{Sfn|Punk Rock Movie 1977}}  "Garageland" is also featured on some live and compilation albums, most notably on ''[[Clash on Broadway]]'' and ''[[The Essential Clash]]'', both released in 2003,{{Sfn|Clash on Broadway 1991}}{{Sfn|Essential Clash 2004}} ''Rarities'' released in 2003,{{Sfn|Rarities 2003}} and ''Pearl Harbour '79'' released in 1979 in Japan and in 2004 worldwide.{{Sfn|Pearl Harbour 79 2004}}

==Reception==
Ironically, only two years after the 1976 review that inspired the band to write "Garageland", in ''[[NME]]'' Murray called The Clash  "the greatest rock band in the world".{{Sfn|Screen on the Green}}

==Tributes==
"Garageland" is also featured on [[tribute album]]s such as ''[[City Rockers: A Tribute To The Clash]]'', released on 6 July 1999 by various artists throughout Chord Records where the song was performed by [[Dozer|The Sick]]. ''White Riot: A Tribute To The Clash (Vol. Two)'' released in 2003 by various artists and performed by [[Billy Bragg]] with Wiggy, [[The Newtown Neurotics|The Neurotics]], and [[Attila the Stockbroker|Attila & The Stockbroker]], ''Charlie Does Surf: A Tribute To The Clash'' released in 2004 by various artists where the song was performed by The Glasgow Tiki Shakers with Bill McGlynnon guitar, Joyce Seko on bass, and Bruce Graham on drums, and ''Revolution Rock: Joe Strummer Memorial Night At Klubi, Tampere Finland'' released on December 2006 by various artists throughout LampLite Ltd. and performed by The Control with ex-[[Hanoi Rocks]]' Stefan Piesnack and Tumppi Varonen on vocals.

The [[New Zealand]] [[Indie rock|indie rock]] band [[Garageland]],<ref>As stated in [[Garageland]].</ref> as well as a UK magazine published by [[Transition Gallery|Transition Edition]],{{Sfn|Garageland Magazine}} (and a tribute band from Dublin Ireland) are named after this song.

==Covers==
"Garageland" has been performed by a number of bands, including :
* Welsh band [[The Oppressed]] (Oi!)
* English band [[The Housemartins]] (indie pop)
* British band [[Chumbawamba]] (punk rock, world, folk)
* New York band [[Urban Blight (band)|Urban Blight]] (ska, reggae, new jack swing)
* Californian band [[Manic Hispanic]] (punk rock, chicano rock)
* Finnish musician [[Pelle Miljoona]] (punk rock)
* Italian band [[:it:Gang (gruppo musicale)|Gang]] {{it}} (acoustic version)
* Italian band [[:it:Linea (gruppo musicale)|Linea]] {{it}}

